climbs.name: El Camino
climbs.fa: Jeff Hollenbaugh, Kris Erickson, & Alan Oram (Fall 2003)

content.description:
Steep, pumpy route. Climb the large crack and finish on the face.

Descent:

Climb up the easy 8' step, and walk off left.
content.protection: Micro cams and nuts to 1" gear, with a 4-5" piece to protect the opening moves.
content.location: Far end of the grassy ledge, under a left facing corner with an offwidth crack.

content.description:
Looking up at this blank face produces a strong sense of incredulity that this thing was once upon a time led. Delicate face moves lead to a thin crack system about halfway up the face.

Descent:

Hike up the grassy ramp, climb up the 8' step, and then walk off left. Reverse these directions for setting a TR anchor. or use extreme caution hiking all the way down the grassy ramp. It is steep, and the grass is slippery, even when dry.
content.protection: Protection is almost comical on this thing. There are a few thin seams up top for gear. You are basically soloing if you lead this. Tree anchor.
content.location: Left hand side of the Livingston Blvd wall. About 20' left of the wide crack that is the start of El Camino.
